1
00:05:37,733 --> 00:05:38,133
[SPEAKER_05]: Hello.

2
00:05:38,734 --> 00:05:39,294
[SPEAKER_05]: Good evening.

3
00:05:39,534 --> 00:05:45,418
[SPEAKER_05]: This is a meeting of the Public Health and Community Safety Committee.

4
00:05:47,199 --> 00:05:50,441
[SPEAKER_05]: June 16th, 6.30 p.m.

5
00:05:52,983 --> 00:06:03,430
[SPEAKER_05]: We are meeting today to talk about the Citizen Control over Public Surveillance report from the Medford Police Department.

6
00:06:05,350 --> 00:06:19,621
[SPEAKER_05]: We received this report in May and we are here today to ask a few questions that we have still from that time.

7
00:06:20,562 --> 00:06:24,545
[SPEAKER_05]: And we discussed this just a little bit.

8
00:06:25,826 --> 00:06:33,172
[SPEAKER_05]: The 2025 annual surveillance report was sent by Chief Buckley every year

9
00:06:33,734 --> 00:06:43,896
[SPEAKER_05]: There's a required report that goes over the police use of body cameras, which is a program that this department's been using for a few years.

10
00:06:44,356 --> 00:06:55,278
[SPEAKER_05]: And we had a report last year that discussed the opportunities and challenges and what was working.

11
00:06:55,578 --> 00:07:01,039
[SPEAKER_05]: And this report is, the intention of the report is to address why

12
00:07:03,592 --> 00:07:25,817
[SPEAKER_05]: to make sure that there aren't situations where any branch of our local government may be inadvertently storing or using data that surveils our residents unnecessarily.

13
00:07:28,759 --> 00:07:31,440
[SPEAKER_05]: The report answers a few questions.

14
00:07:31,480 --> 00:07:35,002
[SPEAKER_05]: This report is publicly available for anybody who might be interested in reading it.

15
00:07:35,963 --> 00:07:38,424
[SPEAKER_05]: I won't read through it now because it's many pages.

16
00:07:39,905 --> 00:07:48,109
[SPEAKER_05]: But if anybody is interested in reading it, it is available on the City Council page of the Medford City website.

17
00:07:49,930 --> 00:07:58,114
[SPEAKER_05]: I would now like to offer City Councilors an opportunity to comment on the report or

18
00:07:58,919 --> 00:07:59,540
[SPEAKER_05]: ask any questions.

19
00:07:59,560 --> 00:08:05,167
[SPEAKER_05]: We do have three representatives from the Medford Police Department here that may be able to address any questions that may come up on the report.

20
00:08:06,870 --> 00:08:16,423
[SPEAKER_05]: And actually, I would also like to offer the police department an opportunity to give a summary, quick summary of the report if you would be comfortable doing so.

21
00:08:17,903 --> 00:08:21,326
[SPEAKER_05]: just because, you know, we wouldn't want to read, like, a six-page report into the record.

22
00:08:23,587 --> 00:08:43,219
[SPEAKER_05]: Any changes that were notable from last year, anything that's improved or changed specifically over the last year, or anything that's notable, continued challenge, perhaps,

23
00:08:45,365 --> 00:08:47,189
[SPEAKER_05]: So Chief Buckley, Jack Buckley is here.

24
00:08:47,209 --> 00:08:55,565
[SPEAKER_05]: If you want to pick up the mic and put it on the higher part of the pedestal, that tends to work if people are taller, a little bit better to pick up your voice.

25
00:08:57,593 --> 00:08:58,574
[SPEAKER_05]: I know it's a little challenging.

26
00:08:58,594 --> 00:08:59,295
[SPEAKER_02]: Does that work?

27
00:08:59,796 --> 00:09:00,877
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes, I think so.

28
00:09:00,897 --> 00:09:05,762
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, so if you can just give us a little summary, that would be great.

29
00:09:06,583 --> 00:09:06,804
[SPEAKER_02]: Sure.

30
00:09:06,984 --> 00:09:10,107
[SPEAKER_02]: So the annual surveillance report was submitted in May.

31
00:09:10,688 --> 00:09:14,553
[SPEAKER_02]: We answered the nine questions as per ordinance.

32
00:09:15,313 --> 00:09:17,616
[SPEAKER_02]: And for the most part, the surveillance technology that we use

33
00:09:18,477 --> 00:09:20,118
[SPEAKER_02]: commonly is our body-worn cameras.

34
00:09:20,198 --> 00:09:24,039
[SPEAKER_02]: I think everybody at this point in time kind of knows what body-worn cameras are, how they work.

35
00:09:24,959 --> 00:09:34,343
[SPEAKER_02]: We see it as one of the advantages of policing, the newer technology that has helped policing and helped the residents and

36
00:09:35,503 --> 00:09:38,885
[SPEAKER_02]: individuals who come to work, play, and reside in the City of Medford.

37
00:09:39,345 --> 00:09:47,228
[SPEAKER_02]: So, Bodywood Camera captures the audio and video footage of most civilian and police officer interactions and relations.

38
00:09:48,029 --> 00:09:49,149
[SPEAKER_02]: During calendar year 2025,

39
00:09:51,410 --> 00:09:53,911
[SPEAKER_02]: Medford police officers made 32,181 videos, of which 1,717 were related to arrests.

40
00:09:53,931 --> 00:09:57,653
[SPEAKER_02]: There were 906 videos related to incidents involving felony, and 1,861 videos involving misdemeanors.

41
00:09:57,673 --> 00:10:03,295
[SPEAKER_02]: About 3,425 video cases, that could be criminal cases, public records requests, et cetera, that were in there, were generated as a result of our

42
00:10:21,246 --> 00:10:35,420
[SPEAKER_02]: sort of organizing those, and there were a separate 361 public records requests, mostly from the district attorney's office, but prosecuting agencies would be requesting those, most of our public records requests.

43
00:10:37,885 --> 00:10:55,321
[SPEAKER_02]: In addition to that, with the public records request, I should note that there are restrictions on public records requests for body-worn camera video footage, and that applies, it's the same restrictions that apply to, say, public records for police reports, where records for,

44
00:10:56,622 --> 00:11:00,944
[SPEAKER_02]: domestic violence, rape, sexual assaults, they are confidential and not public records.

45
00:11:00,984 --> 00:11:07,928
[SPEAKER_02]: So those body-worn camera video footages would not be disseminated by public records request, even if we get said public records request.

46
00:11:08,748 --> 00:11:17,293
[SPEAKER_02]: And so you could see there were nine times that that happened where people submitted a request for body-worn camera footage and we denied their because of the law, the request.

47
00:11:17,893 --> 00:11:27,039
[SPEAKER_02]: There was also nine other of the requests that were denied of the approximately 108 public records requests, and those were related to arrests.

48
00:11:27,259 --> 00:11:31,102
[SPEAKER_02]: And the best way to describe this is an individual gets arrested on Friday.

49
00:11:31,162 --> 00:11:37,346
[SPEAKER_02]: By Monday morning, they're requesting their body-worn camera video footage that has already been turned over to the prosecutor.

50
00:11:38,106 --> 00:11:40,688
[SPEAKER_02]: They get it through their defense attorney that they include anyway.

51
00:11:41,448 --> 00:11:54,442
[SPEAKER_02]: It saves everyone a whole lot of time to just say go through the court system with your defense attorney because all of our body-worn cameras related to any criminal event is turned over to the district attorney and subsequently going through the discovery process given to all defendants in a case.

52
00:12:00,954 --> 00:12:03,236
[SPEAKER_02]: That's sort of the crux of the body-worn camera.

53
00:12:03,256 --> 00:12:06,899
[SPEAKER_02]: That's our primary use of surveillance technology.

54
00:12:07,699 --> 00:12:13,343
[SPEAKER_02]: This year, we are reporting that at least in one criminal case, we used GPS to track it.

55
00:12:13,444 --> 00:12:17,807
[SPEAKER_02]: Again, I'm not going to get into any of these criminal investigations, but it was court-ordered.

56
00:12:18,527 --> 00:12:20,369
[SPEAKER_02]: We put a GPS device on.

57
00:12:22,390 --> 00:12:25,493
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm trying to carefully walk my way through this.

58
00:12:25,513 --> 00:12:28,776
[SPEAKER_02]: We used the GPS in the criminal investigation per court order.

59
00:12:29,477 --> 00:12:35,382
[SPEAKER_02]: And in addition to that, there were three identifiable times

60
00:12:36,105 --> 00:12:41,726
[SPEAKER_02]: where we use facial recognition technology, and that was in compliance with other police agencies.

61
00:12:41,806 --> 00:12:51,249
[SPEAKER_02]: But also, anytime we use facial recognition, we are bound by the restrictions of Mass General Law, Chapter 6, Section 220, which outlines how police departments can use facial recognition.

62
00:12:51,909 --> 00:12:56,670
[SPEAKER_02]: And were we, I mean, I guess the oversight to that comes with the court systems, right?

63
00:12:56,690 --> 00:13:02,231
[SPEAKER_02]: So if we were to probably use facial recognition, we would know by the judges and the defense attorneys, et cetera.

64
00:13:02,611 --> 00:13:05,672
[SPEAKER_02]: And so there were no issues thus far with using them.

65
00:13:06,472 --> 00:13:15,138
[SPEAKER_02]: And additional to that, there was approximately 12 cases where flock camera evidence was used in criminal investigations with the police department.

66
00:13:15,558 --> 00:13:19,941
[SPEAKER_02]: Now, I'll say publicly because I know everyone here realizes and understands we do not have flock cameras.

67
00:13:20,001 --> 00:13:20,621
[SPEAKER_02]: We don't have them.

68
00:13:20,641 --> 00:13:21,582
[SPEAKER_02]: We don't maintain them.

69
00:13:21,622 --> 00:13:21,922
[SPEAKER_02]: We don't.

70
00:13:22,422 --> 00:13:25,144
[SPEAKER_02]: administer them, but other communities still don't.

71
00:13:25,404 --> 00:13:38,133
[SPEAKER_02]: And if we say, hey, we're looking for a red Prius in a criminal investigation, and I'll give an example, say the city of Somerville, I don't know if they have law cameras or I do know they have certain cameras, they come back and say, hey, we had a red Prius that was driving down the street.

72
00:13:38,833 --> 00:13:42,255
[SPEAKER_02]: and we captured this plate at this certain time, it matches up to criminal.

73
00:13:42,275 --> 00:13:47,036
[SPEAKER_02]: So we will use that information as evidence in our criminal investigation.

74
00:13:47,196 --> 00:13:51,158
[SPEAKER_02]: And again, evidence isn't always used to convict somebody.

75
00:13:51,218 --> 00:13:53,399
[SPEAKER_02]: It's also used to prove innocence of people.

76
00:13:53,519 --> 00:14:01,242
[SPEAKER_02]: So those are the instances that we have used other surveillance technology, even though we don't really own or operate those sorts of technologies.

77
00:14:01,902 --> 00:14:02,662
[SPEAKER_02]: Separate from that,

78
00:14:06,523 --> 00:14:07,924
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm here to answer any other questions.

79
00:14:07,964 --> 00:14:08,824
[SPEAKER_02]: I think it's pretty straight.

80
00:14:08,884 --> 00:14:12,486
[SPEAKER_02]: I think the report reads pretty clearly and straightforward.

81
00:14:12,506 --> 00:14:17,989
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, I will add that, you know, the body one camera program is proceeding.

82
00:14:19,050 --> 00:14:22,432
[SPEAKER_02]: And, you know, we went through a first year of

83
00:14:23,568 --> 00:14:28,231
[SPEAKER_02]: So trial and error, it's a new practice, we put it into play and we had a lot of training and retraining.

84
00:14:28,891 --> 00:14:35,815
[SPEAKER_02]: And last year, somewhere around May, I was here also talking about this and we had some issues that we were dealing with.

85
00:14:36,315 --> 00:14:40,578
[SPEAKER_02]: I believe one of the issues that was brought up at that time was a question of how we redact.

86
00:14:42,253 --> 00:14:48,377
[SPEAKER_02]: And so we will have a package for you later on that shows you that we have a policy now on redaction of body-worn camera.

87
00:14:48,417 --> 00:14:55,483
[SPEAKER_02]: That was a suggestion from the city council at last year's meeting which we implemented shortly thereafter and we follow that.

88
00:14:56,503 --> 00:14:58,405
[SPEAKER_02]: Above and beyond that, so.

89
00:14:59,565 --> 00:15:01,066
[SPEAKER_02]: We collect our body-worn cameras.

90
00:15:01,527 --> 00:15:03,448
[SPEAKER_02]: We store them for certain periods of time.

91
00:15:03,468 --> 00:15:09,453
[SPEAKER_02]: We don't store anything indefinitely unless it's a very, very serious crime or that the courts have ordered us to store them indefinitely.

92
00:15:10,774 --> 00:15:17,159
[SPEAKER_02]: And we, the other things that we do is we do two separate audits of our police officers, right?

93
00:15:17,179 --> 00:15:19,541
[SPEAKER_02]: So we wanna make sure that they're in compliance with policy.

94
00:15:19,901 --> 00:15:23,004
[SPEAKER_02]: So we don't review every body-worn camera video because we can't, right?

95
00:15:23,024 --> 00:15:24,185
[SPEAKER_02]: There's not enough time in the day.

96
00:15:24,685 --> 00:15:27,488
[SPEAKER_02]: So annually we do an audit of our,

97
00:15:28,748 --> 00:15:32,390
[SPEAKER_02]: Camera systems, in general, we take three incidences per officer, right?

98
00:15:32,750 --> 00:15:41,113
[SPEAKER_02]: So it's going to be hard to find three incidences of the chief of police on body-worn camera because that's just not really my job and my technology, but a regular patrol officer will clearly have many of them.

99
00:15:41,673 --> 00:15:54,397
[SPEAKER_02]: So we go through every officer, we review three videos, three separate incidences, say it could be a general incident, a motor vehicle stop, could be an arrest if they had one, and we make sure that they're in compliance with sort of body-worn camera policy and other policies.

100
00:15:54,697 --> 00:15:56,198
[SPEAKER_02]: Additionally, we do another audit.

101
00:15:56,758 --> 00:16:03,362
[SPEAKER_02]: where we review our supervisors, because we have restrictions on who even internally can review body-worn camera footage.

102
00:16:03,942 --> 00:16:14,587
[SPEAKER_02]: And that audit is to make sure, you know, like as a lieutenant, I might have access to body-worn cameras, but if it's not to my shift or my involvement in that case, I shouldn't be reviewing that case.

103
00:16:14,627 --> 00:16:17,009
[SPEAKER_02]: And we do an audit to kind of ensure that that's not happening.

104
00:16:17,629 --> 00:16:20,050
[SPEAKER_02]: So we have a lot of safeguards in place for the technology.

105
00:16:20,110 --> 00:16:28,475
[SPEAKER_02]: It does take a lot of time and a lot of hours to kind of maintain this program, but we feel thus far it's very effective for everyone involved in here.

106
00:16:29,115 --> 00:16:32,537
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think we've fairly outlined that in this report.

107
00:16:33,918 --> 00:16:35,819
[SPEAKER_02]: So any questions, I'll be glad to help.

108
00:16:35,839 --> 00:16:37,100
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you, Chief.

109
00:16:38,160 --> 00:16:41,202
[SPEAKER_05]: As I recall from the report last year, there was a challenge

110
00:16:45,527 --> 00:16:53,294
[SPEAKER_05]: officers that came up in the audit, officers announcing that they were going to turn on their cameras.

111
00:16:53,334 --> 00:16:56,656
[SPEAKER_05]: Was that something that you noticed this time or was that kind of a first year issue?

112
00:16:57,077 --> 00:17:04,683
[SPEAKER_02]: So it is probably one of the regular compliance issues that we still maintain.

113
00:17:05,404 --> 00:17:06,785
[SPEAKER_02]: In the beginning, like I said, these are

114
00:17:07,800 --> 00:17:12,068
[SPEAKER_02]: There were growing pains, per se, and now we still have it, and occasionally it still does happen.

115
00:17:12,729 --> 00:17:20,523
[SPEAKER_02]: But we have instituted other reviews and policies and checks, and I'm trying to think back at what point in time.

116
00:17:22,196 --> 00:17:30,945
[SPEAKER_02]: at 2025, but we did a whole, another sort of update and training and reminder of people to do this, and we have pretty good compliance with that.

117
00:17:30,985 --> 00:17:38,073
[SPEAKER_02]: So, yeah, I think it's going to historically always be with us, like at 3 o'clock in the morning if an officer forgets something, we're going to record that.

118
00:17:38,553 --> 00:17:42,057
[SPEAKER_02]: But we review and make sure that none of this is sort of intentional, right?

119
00:17:42,097 --> 00:17:43,979
[SPEAKER_02]: I think the idea behind body-worn camera,

120
00:17:44,359 --> 00:17:51,583
[SPEAKER_02]: or at least the way the law is written is we want to make sure the police officers aren't intentionally not recording things, and we don't see any evidence of that, right?

121
00:17:51,603 --> 00:17:59,647
[SPEAKER_02]: So occasionally we get somebody who turns it on too late, turns it off too early, or may have forgotten to turn on the body-worn camera.

122
00:18:00,227 --> 00:18:06,850
[SPEAKER_02]: So it still sort of is an issue, but we are improving on that as the standard as we mentioned last year, we were going to improve on that standard.

123
00:18:13,450 --> 00:18:14,611
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, I have three questions.

124
00:18:14,811 --> 00:18:15,932
[SPEAKER_06]: I'll just do one at a time.

125
00:18:15,952 --> 00:18:16,552
[SPEAKER_06]: It's a little easier.

126
00:18:17,553 --> 00:18:19,975
[SPEAKER_06]: So how would people file complaints?

127
00:18:20,015 --> 00:18:22,537
[SPEAKER_06]: Like what's the process for filing a complaint?

128
00:18:23,477 --> 00:18:25,178
[SPEAKER_02]: Just in general or like related to the technology?

129
00:18:25,218 --> 00:18:29,261
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, so under number five, a summary of complaints or concerns that were received about the surveillance technology.

130
00:18:29,301 --> 00:18:32,324
[SPEAKER_06]: Like how would those complaints, like what would be the process for that to happen?

131
00:18:34,786 --> 00:18:40,112
[SPEAKER_02]: This is not as, it's a simple process, but it's not as simple as to be able to kind of describe it.

132
00:18:40,132 --> 00:18:40,893
[SPEAKER_02]: There's multiple ways.

133
00:18:41,493 --> 00:18:44,577
[SPEAKER_02]: So, in general, they can show up in person, right?

134
00:18:44,857 --> 00:18:48,481
[SPEAKER_02]: They can speak to the commanding officer of the shift, and they will be given an opportunity to be heard.

135
00:18:48,721 --> 00:18:50,023
[SPEAKER_02]: They'll fill out a complaint form.

136
00:18:50,643 --> 00:18:58,610
[SPEAKER_02]: And anytime we receive a complaint within 48 hours, we have to notify the state, the post commission, and then we do an investigation on those sort of complaints, right?

137
00:18:59,991 --> 00:19:05,275
[SPEAKER_02]: We also can, an individual can also file online and file a complaint, in which case,

138
00:19:06,187 --> 00:19:08,229
[SPEAKER_02]: When we get that, we will do sort of the reverse.

139
00:19:08,289 --> 00:19:13,973
[SPEAKER_02]: We have a professional standards division who might have to reach out to that individual, follow up, and say, hey, I'd like to talk to you about this.

140
00:19:14,034 --> 00:19:14,814
[SPEAKER_02]: Will you have a complaint?

141
00:19:15,134 --> 00:19:18,978
[SPEAKER_02]: They can either meet in person or do an interview over the phone to file that complaint.

142
00:19:19,858 --> 00:19:25,423
[SPEAKER_02]: And then there's another option where simply they can go directly to the Mass Post Commission to file a complaint on anything.

143
00:19:25,443 --> 00:19:27,805
[SPEAKER_02]: And they can just go online to file a complaint.

144
00:19:27,825 --> 00:19:33,450
[SPEAKER_02]: And that's just, that is body, word, and camera related complaints, but it could be any complaint for any of those issues.

145
00:19:34,143 --> 00:19:34,363
[SPEAKER_06]: Thanks.

146
00:19:35,683 --> 00:19:39,024
[SPEAKER_06]: My second question is, yeah, it's about violations.

147
00:19:39,044 --> 00:19:40,884
[SPEAKER_06]: There were no violations observed or reported.

148
00:19:40,904 --> 00:19:52,426
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm just curious, like, can you give us a few examples of what violations could be, and do you expect in any one given year, do you expect to have a few, or I'm just a little bit curious about the violations and what they would be.

149
00:19:54,267 --> 00:20:02,348
[SPEAKER_02]: Sure, and I don't know if you're referring to, or if you want me to try to reference any specific violation, but again, as I mentioned, a lot of the violations will be

150
00:20:03,606 --> 00:20:13,896
[SPEAKER_02]: like failure to turn your body one camera on in a call or turning it on too late or turning it off too early as I mentioned just a few seconds ago.

151
00:20:14,376 --> 00:20:17,319
[SPEAKER_02]: Those are in generally our biggest sort of

152
00:20:18,345 --> 00:20:20,966
[SPEAKER_02]: by far our largest sort of complaint and issues.

153
00:20:21,526 --> 00:20:28,108
[SPEAKER_02]: And let me mention that any time somebody has a failure or a discrepancy, they're required to fill out a report.

154
00:20:28,568 --> 00:20:37,811
[SPEAKER_02]: So like it's a user report that says so that the body-worn camera division knows that there was a discrepancy and they can follow up and find out like what happened.

155
00:20:38,351 --> 00:20:45,173
[SPEAKER_02]: Sometimes it's just an honest mistake, an innocent mistake, and we kind of have to, again, backing up to what I said earlier, we have to rule out any intention to it.

156
00:20:46,825 --> 00:21:06,603
[SPEAKER_02]: Also, it should be mentioned that, especially if the case rises to the level of a criminal investigation that might end up in the courts, police officers, when they write their incident reports and their arrest reports, will mention that this incident was captured on body-worn camera, or if not, it was not.

157
00:21:07,807 --> 00:21:12,250
[SPEAKER_02]: mention of audio camera, but there will be a discrepancy report that was filed with that to kind of keep track of that.

158
00:21:13,191 --> 00:21:30,862
[SPEAKER_02]: And so, but I think by far, I would tell you that the incidences of, just looking for the policy here, what else we would have, it's clearly those are the biggest incidences that we have, is just the timeliness and filing of the camera.

159
00:21:31,462 --> 00:21:35,625
[SPEAKER_02]: Sometimes you get out in mayhem and you've got to do this, you actually have to hit the camera

160
00:21:36,979 --> 00:21:37,379
[SPEAKER_02]: You forget.

161
00:21:37,820 --> 00:21:44,404
[SPEAKER_02]: And what's kind of curious is we still count it as a violation, but let's say, you know, you and I showed up as a scene, we're both police officers.

162
00:21:44,905 --> 00:21:48,547
[SPEAKER_02]: It's still a violation if I don't turn my body and my camera on, but you might have captured everything.

163
00:21:48,927 --> 00:21:53,991
[SPEAKER_02]: We don't say, oh, it's on, because there's multiple officers sometimes almost on every scene.

164
00:21:54,051 --> 00:22:03,778
[SPEAKER_02]: So in some version we get it, but we still make and require the officer who did turn their camera on to file a report on it, a separate report on it.

165
00:22:04,337 --> 00:22:04,557
[SPEAKER_06]: Great.

166
00:22:04,637 --> 00:22:11,584
[SPEAKER_06]: And do you, I only asked because I was slightly surprised to see that no violations observed or reported.

167
00:22:11,624 --> 00:22:20,031
[SPEAKER_06]: Like I would imagine that, especially because it's a new-ish program, it's only the second year of the program, that there would be some violations.

168
00:22:20,532 --> 00:22:29,740
[SPEAKER_06]: So I was wondering if there were like any that you would, like would you anticipate four or five or ten or something each year from newer officers or from, you know,

169
00:22:31,050 --> 00:22:32,653
[SPEAKER_02]: And are you referring to question six?

170
00:22:32,673 --> 00:22:34,736
[SPEAKER_06]: Number six, I think, I apologize.

171
00:22:35,037 --> 00:22:36,339
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, and that's that's for the audit.

172
00:22:36,499 --> 00:22:36,740
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes.

173
00:22:37,201 --> 00:22:38,783
[SPEAKER_02]: So and again, the audit is of.

174
00:22:40,574 --> 00:22:43,196
[SPEAKER_02]: It's not every video recording.

175
00:22:43,296 --> 00:22:48,198
[SPEAKER_02]: And we, like I said, on a daily basis, we know if somebody made an error because it's self-reported.

176
00:22:48,678 --> 00:22:56,263
[SPEAKER_02]: But we'll take, say we have 100 police officers, we'll do three videos of every single officer who may have them and go through that.

177
00:22:56,403 --> 00:23:00,485
[SPEAKER_02]: And yeah, they're, you know, we're looking at body-worn camera policy mostly.

178
00:23:00,665 --> 00:23:05,247
[SPEAKER_02]: Of course, we're not going to ignore something that we blatantly see wrong, right, which we haven't, but yeah.

179
00:23:05,647 --> 00:23:08,329
[SPEAKER_02]: And, you know, I have Officer Casarino,

180
00:23:09,593 --> 00:23:11,375
[SPEAKER_02]: He does that audit, and he's one of them.

181
00:23:11,415 --> 00:23:13,156
[SPEAKER_02]: We have a lieutenant, and there's no report.

182
00:23:13,777 --> 00:23:16,459
[SPEAKER_02]: We're getting really good at this, and it's not...

183
00:23:19,133 --> 00:23:25,136
[SPEAKER_02]: I guess the best way to say this, and you could see it in every other police agency, is just, like, I still have a habit to this day.

184
00:23:25,397 --> 00:23:30,960
[SPEAKER_02]: I touch this radio, and I turn it on and off, because if your radio is on when you step into a cruise, you get two different things in your skull.

185
00:23:30,980 --> 00:23:33,561
[SPEAKER_02]: So every time I step in a car, I'm turning this thing down.

186
00:23:34,001 --> 00:23:35,522
[SPEAKER_02]: It's a habit I have for 28 years.

187
00:23:35,902 --> 00:23:41,606
[SPEAKER_02]: Body-worn cameras and the touching of that are becoming a habit of police officers, just sort of instinctive.

188
00:23:42,466 --> 00:23:43,907
[SPEAKER_02]: Sometimes you still forget that, right?

189
00:23:44,047 --> 00:23:47,309
[SPEAKER_02]: Like, and so, but yeah, as far as our articles, yeah, it's nothing.

190
00:23:48,253 --> 00:23:51,075
[SPEAKER_02]: And I mean, if you need me, I can have Officer Casarito come up.

191
00:23:51,256 --> 00:23:57,361
[SPEAKER_02]: I know he loves to be in the public limelight, but he does the audits along with Lieutenant Duffy, and there's no reported issues.

192
00:23:58,884 --> 00:24:09,008
[SPEAKER_06]: Great, so it sounds like there is a difference between the violations that come out of the audit and the violations that I just imagined.

193
00:24:09,028 --> 00:24:13,050
[SPEAKER_06]: And I remember there was some sort of a graph, like a chart or something last year.

194
00:24:13,070 --> 00:24:14,371
[SPEAKER_02]: So keep in mind, yeah, correct.

195
00:24:14,751 --> 00:24:16,332
[SPEAKER_02]: So keep in mind, there could be, right?

196
00:24:16,712 --> 00:24:25,816
[SPEAKER_02]: So if the number one violation is failure to, let's say the number one violation is failure to turn on your bodywork camera, well, we can't audit that because it doesn't exist.

197
00:24:26,837 --> 00:24:30,703
[SPEAKER_02]: So we're only auditing a video that exists.

198
00:24:31,244 --> 00:24:36,774
[SPEAKER_06]: But you probably somewhere have those because they write them down, but they don't appear in this report.

199
00:24:36,814 --> 00:24:37,816
[SPEAKER_02]: Is that accurate?

200
00:24:39,249 --> 00:24:46,798
[SPEAKER_02]: They don't appear in that report, but we produce an annual body-worn camera report that will have certain, like, this is how many videos and this and that, and so I can get you a copy of that tonight.

201
00:24:47,539 --> 00:24:48,000
[SPEAKER_06]: Wonderful.

202
00:24:48,120 --> 00:24:53,686
[SPEAKER_06]: And is that something that normally comes up at the same time, or is that, like that body-worn camera report, is that the same time?

203
00:24:53,706 --> 00:24:56,730
[SPEAKER_02]: That's an internal document we do ourselves as part of, so.

204
00:24:57,591 --> 00:25:07,314
[SPEAKER_02]: the team that I have on 41 cameras reports directly to the Office of the Chief of Police and they'll do these audits in an annual report to kind of keep me up to date.

205
00:25:07,334 --> 00:25:20,078
[SPEAKER_02]: I get a monthly report, I get an annual report, and they send it to me and we kind of, you know, it's not part of the CCOPS ordinance, it's not really part of the questions that we're required to answer, but it's just an internal way that we keep track of what's happening on the police department.

206
00:25:21,358 --> 00:25:23,939
[SPEAKER_02]: I probably get way too many reports, but this is one that we use.

207
00:25:24,902 --> 00:25:27,683
[SPEAKER_02]: That's how we can judge and tell what's going on and what's happening.

208
00:25:28,064 --> 00:25:28,664
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay, thanks.

209
00:25:29,264 --> 00:25:51,656
[SPEAKER_06]: My third question is about just, so I'm curious about instances when, and please tell me if it is covered in here and maybe I didn't pick up on it, but instances where police, anyone from the department would view the body-worn camera footage after the fact?

210
00:25:52,936 --> 00:25:56,399
[SPEAKER_06]: Is that something that is tracked, maybe in the document you just referenced?

211
00:25:56,439 --> 00:25:58,120
[SPEAKER_06]: Is it something that appears in this report?

212
00:25:59,481 --> 00:26:07,448
[SPEAKER_06]: Like, I'm assuming that that's generally, there's a policy that that doesn't happen, but I'm just kind of curious about that piece of it, if you can talk, speak to that.

213
00:26:08,649 --> 00:26:12,712
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, so it's a larger question than I think you even imagine.

214
00:26:12,732 --> 00:26:16,775
[SPEAKER_02]: So if I, let's say, go to a motor vehicle accident,

215
00:26:17,433 --> 00:26:21,737
[SPEAKER_02]: and I have my body-worn camera, when I'm writing that report, I have access to view my body-worn camera.

216
00:26:22,157 --> 00:26:26,981
[SPEAKER_02]: I can, by policy, I can review my body-worn camera and write reports, et cetera.

217
00:26:27,442 --> 00:26:40,673
[SPEAKER_02]: If we have an incident where an officer fills out, say, like a use of force report, the supervisor of that shift and that officer's supervisor is actually sergeants and lieutenants have access to look at that body-worn camera and review that.

218
00:26:41,413 --> 00:26:47,476
[SPEAKER_02]: Anytime somebody accesses a body-worn camera video is, I forget the term for it, but basically it's an electronic signature.

219
00:26:47,516 --> 00:26:48,617
[SPEAKER_02]: We know who's watching what.

220
00:26:48,997 --> 00:26:51,798
[SPEAKER_02]: And that was part of the supervisory audit that I had mentioned earlier.

221
00:26:52,279 --> 00:26:55,340
[SPEAKER_02]: So we know when people are watching videos and who's watching them.

222
00:26:55,981 --> 00:26:57,041
[SPEAKER_06]: That's really helpful to know.

223
00:26:57,061 --> 00:26:57,882
[SPEAKER_06]: I like that.

224
00:26:57,982 --> 00:26:58,582
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

225
00:26:58,602 --> 00:26:58,882
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

226
00:26:59,002 --> 00:27:01,723
[SPEAKER_02]: And so it is, again, part of the secondary audit.

227
00:27:02,504 --> 00:27:07,727
[SPEAKER_02]: We also, you know, in a criminal, and I'm just kind of expanding this to give a clearer picture.

228
00:27:10,320 --> 00:27:22,189
[SPEAKER_02]: if there is a criminal investigation that results as a, that comes about as a result of a police interaction on, say, like this evening, detectives will also have access because they're investigating that criminal.

229
00:27:22,229 --> 00:27:23,670
[SPEAKER_02]: They would be able to sort of look at that.

230
00:27:24,450 --> 00:27:25,951
[SPEAKER_02]: And professional standards, of course.

231
00:27:26,572 --> 00:27:33,937
[SPEAKER_02]: I very rarely look at a body-worn camera video footage because there's no real need for me to look at it, unless there's a need for me to look at it, if that made some sense.

232
00:27:34,438 --> 00:27:37,240
[SPEAKER_02]: But we have staff that are put in place, and it just kind of restricts.

233
00:27:38,281 --> 00:27:40,885
[SPEAKER_02]: It's not out there for entertainment purposes internally.

234
00:27:42,568 --> 00:27:44,772
[SPEAKER_02]: Very few people have access and we do keep track of that.

235
00:27:44,912 --> 00:27:45,714
[SPEAKER_02]: And we can't find out.

236
00:27:47,396 --> 00:27:48,216
[SPEAKER_06]: That's super helpful.

237
00:27:48,236 --> 00:27:48,717
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you so much.

238
00:27:48,797 --> 00:27:49,718
[SPEAKER_06]: It really is.

239
00:27:50,799 --> 00:27:57,165
[SPEAKER_06]: It's good to understand kind of that there's like very clear policies on like when they can be reviewed.

240
00:27:57,245 --> 00:28:00,368
[SPEAKER_06]: And you know I'm sure that they are quite useful when you're writing your report.

241
00:28:01,449 --> 00:28:02,971
[SPEAKER_02]: It's yeah it's beneficial.

242
00:28:03,011 --> 00:28:04,012
[SPEAKER_02]: That's for certain.

243
00:28:04,852 --> 00:28:09,116
[SPEAKER_02]: And as I mentioned I think I mentioned this last year but definitely the first year.

244
00:28:09,737 --> 00:28:21,682
[SPEAKER_02]: We're finding more and more the district attorneys and at least through the district attorney in Middlesex County, prosecutors, defense attorneys and judges are now saying we prefer the officer to watch their body on camera video.

245
00:28:23,023 --> 00:28:26,965
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, there's a legal side of that and everything else like that but it is beneficial, right?

246
00:28:28,385 --> 00:28:32,427
[SPEAKER_02]: And we have not had any instances of issues with that when it comes out.

247
00:28:33,548 --> 00:28:33,808
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

248
00:28:42,890 --> 00:28:45,292
[SPEAKER_05]: Are there any other questions from counselors?

249
00:28:47,914 --> 00:28:51,296
[SPEAKER_05]: Seeing none, do you have anything else you want to say about?

250
00:28:51,397 --> 00:28:51,617
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

251
00:28:51,637 --> 00:28:52,577
[SPEAKER_02]: Whatever you need from me, I'll.

252
00:28:52,718 --> 00:28:52,978
[SPEAKER_05]: Great.

253
00:28:54,919 --> 00:28:55,139
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

254
00:28:55,219 --> 00:28:57,621
[SPEAKER_05]: I would like to open it up to public comment.

255
00:28:59,283 --> 00:29:03,706
[SPEAKER_05]: We have a, yes, if you'd like to come to the podium and give us your name for the record.

256
00:29:05,402 --> 00:29:05,882
[SPEAKER_00]: Good evening.

257
00:29:06,663 --> 00:29:09,165
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm Jean Zotter, 36 Saunders Street.

258
00:29:11,067 --> 00:29:15,510
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm with Medford People Power and we advocated for this ordinance.

259
00:29:17,772 --> 00:29:25,979
[SPEAKER_00]: And we want to thank the committee for making this, holding this forum to provide public comment on the annual surveillance report.

260
00:29:26,577 --> 00:29:32,139
[SPEAKER_00]: We want to thank the police department for submitting the annual report, although we hope next time it's on time.

261
00:29:33,500 --> 00:29:35,621
[SPEAKER_00]: Just a quiet request.

262
00:29:36,041 --> 00:29:39,022
[SPEAKER_00]: I just want to say a little bit about why this is important.

263
00:29:39,843 --> 00:29:53,969
[SPEAKER_00]: I think we've seen over the past couple of years how surveillance technology can be misused when it comes to ICE officers using it to track down people in their homes, and the laws have not caught up

264
00:29:54,379 --> 00:29:56,000
[SPEAKER_00]: with this type of technology.

265
00:29:56,560 --> 00:30:00,141
[SPEAKER_00]: So warrants aren't required for a lot of surveillance technology that's allowed.

266
00:30:02,302 --> 00:30:04,783
[SPEAKER_00]: And so it's important that Medford have this.

267
00:30:05,163 --> 00:30:11,445
[SPEAKER_00]: And I just want to remind us why we're doing this, because I know it could be a lot of work for the police department and a lot of work for this committee.

268
00:30:13,305 --> 00:30:18,247
[SPEAKER_00]: And one of the CCOPS came up around the Black Lives Matter movement.

269
00:30:19,428 --> 00:30:23,009
[SPEAKER_00]: And this was a way to ensure police accountability.

270
00:30:24,149 --> 00:30:32,178
[SPEAKER_00]: And so that's one thing that we see this ordinance doing is to make sure that police are accountable to the public.

271
00:30:32,999 --> 00:30:38,805
[SPEAKER_00]: And also body worn cameras were something that came up as a source of holding police accountable to the public.

272
00:30:39,766 --> 00:30:53,656
[SPEAKER_00]: And that was a reason, I remember we were at a Martin Luther King event and Chief Buckley was there and we were talking about some of the recent murders that happened of black people by police.

273
00:30:54,197 --> 00:30:58,560
[SPEAKER_00]: And this was something that was mentioned as a way to hold police accountable in Medford.

274
00:30:59,263 --> 00:31:06,466
[SPEAKER_00]: not saying that anything has happened in Medford where this is needed, but it is good to be proactive to ensure that we have this type of accountability.

275
00:31:07,566 --> 00:31:26,913
[SPEAKER_00]: There has also been recent instances of misuse of body-worn camera where there has been, not in Medford, but instances of police looking up their ex-wives, looking up girlfriends, tracking where people are, using body-worn camera footage.

276
00:31:26,993 --> 00:31:27,634
[SPEAKER_00]: So it's just,

277
00:31:28,514 --> 00:31:33,518
[SPEAKER_00]: good to make sure that we're staying on top of this technology and tracking what's going on.

278
00:31:34,518 --> 00:31:41,163
[SPEAKER_00]: So with that in mind, I think Barry has some questions he's going to ask, and I just want to focus on two issues of privacy and accountability.

279
00:31:44,019 --> 00:31:52,244
[SPEAKER_00]: We just always want to make sure that the privacy of Medford residents is protected with the use of surveillance technology.

280
00:31:52,264 --> 00:32:05,532
[SPEAKER_00]: Our main concern is that any surveillance technology that we have is not used as a general surveillance tool outside of investigation of crimes and that the privacy of residents is protected.

281
00:32:07,633 --> 00:32:13,295
[SPEAKER_00]: The report details the use of body-worn cameras primarily for case investigation.

282
00:32:14,295 --> 00:32:20,136
[SPEAKER_00]: However, we would like to see more information about how they're protecting the privacy of residents.

283
00:32:20,196 --> 00:32:26,578
[SPEAKER_00]: It's good to know, and I know in the body-worn camera policy there's information about storage of data.

284
00:32:27,938 --> 00:32:35,940
[SPEAKER_00]: It would just be nice to hear how, when data is going to be destroyed, how they're protecting the data itself.

285
00:32:37,141 --> 00:32:46,650
[SPEAKER_00]: The second thing is accountability, and so the chief did mention there's two audits, and in the report it says that there were no findings.

286
00:32:47,731 --> 00:32:49,132
[SPEAKER_00]: It was really helpful last time.

287
00:32:49,152 --> 00:32:57,460
[SPEAKER_00]: The report had both the results of the audit, but also a breakdown of special notification forms, which I think is when

288
00:32:58,030 --> 00:33:00,091
[SPEAKER_00]: body worn cameras aren't turned on or off.

289
00:33:00,531 --> 00:33:06,975
[SPEAKER_00]: So it would be helpful to see whether those whether that's getting improved or not.

290
00:33:07,235 --> 00:33:13,658
[SPEAKER_00]: And, um, are there instances of special notification forms being issued?

291
00:33:14,759 --> 00:33:16,920
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, you asked a lot of our questions.

292
00:33:16,980 --> 00:33:17,980
[SPEAKER_00]: Counselor Callahan.

293
00:33:18,400 --> 00:33:18,981
[SPEAKER_00]: So thank you.

294
00:33:19,901 --> 00:33:26,885
[SPEAKER_00]: I think the only other question we have is, has there ever been an instance of an officer who is allowed to review footage

295
00:33:27,605 --> 00:33:36,831
[SPEAKER_00]: before making a statement prior to possible, in a case of possible misconduct by that officer?

296
00:33:37,432 --> 00:33:43,556
[SPEAKER_00]: So we know that they can, the chief detailed how they can review footage prior to a case that's going to court.

297
00:33:43,596 --> 00:33:45,017
[SPEAKER_00]: The DA is asking for that.

298
00:33:45,557 --> 00:33:50,961
[SPEAKER_00]: But has there been a case where an officer is allowed to review footage if there is a case of misconduct?

299
00:33:51,341 --> 00:33:53,262
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's the only question I have.

300
00:33:53,682 --> 00:33:54,583
[SPEAKER_00]: I know Barry has some more.

301
00:33:55,804 --> 00:33:56,044
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

302
00:33:58,919 --> 00:33:59,279
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

303
00:34:02,182 --> 00:34:06,507
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm just checking on Zoom for any other comments.

304
00:34:06,527 --> 00:34:08,389
[SPEAKER_05]: Seeing none, go back to the podium.

305
00:34:09,830 --> 00:34:11,672
[SPEAKER_01]: For short people.

306
00:34:12,473 --> 00:34:13,974
[SPEAKER_05]: And you can give your name for the record, please.

307
00:34:15,155 --> 00:34:17,818
[SPEAKER_01]: Barry Ingber, 9 Draper Street in Medford.

308
00:34:19,320 --> 00:34:22,162
[SPEAKER_01]: I guess I have a question on process for the chair first.

309
00:34:23,853 --> 00:34:35,999
[SPEAKER_01]: I have a lot of questions and Jean just asked one, and if it's okay with you and if it's okay with the chief to have a dialogue to get those answers would probably be helpful.

310
00:34:36,019 --> 00:34:42,942
[SPEAKER_01]: But if that's not consistent with how you see process, just please advise me on how you'd rather I do it.

311
00:34:42,962 --> 00:34:53,347
[SPEAKER_05]: If you wouldn't mind presenting the questions to me, then we can offer an opportunity for the police department to field the questions once your comment period is over.

312
00:34:53,627 --> 00:34:54,007
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

313
00:34:54,047 --> 00:34:54,508
[SPEAKER_05]: Concluded.

314
00:34:55,668 --> 00:35:02,213
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'm going to restrict my comments and questions to section 1B of the annual surveillance report.

315
00:35:03,273 --> 00:35:11,098
[SPEAKER_01]: And I appreciate Chief Buckley for being upfront about the use of surveillance technologies other than body-worn cameras in his report.

316
00:35:11,799 --> 00:35:16,542
[SPEAKER_01]: So note that, Chief Buckley, I just appreciated it.

317
00:35:19,900 --> 00:35:35,968
[SPEAKER_01]: The report states that these tools, specifically GPS trackers, flock data from other municipalities, and facial recognition technology from other law enforcement agencies, were used, quote, in accordance with applicable legal authority.

318
00:35:37,088 --> 00:35:44,912
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'm just wondering what authority is meant, since these tools are restricted by law under CCOPS.

319
00:35:45,843 --> 00:35:54,045
[SPEAKER_01]: and wondering if there were any exigent uses of those technologies, which is an exception granted in CCOPS.

320
00:35:56,325 --> 00:35:57,845
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's the first set of questions.

321
00:35:58,245 --> 00:35:59,125
[SPEAKER_05]: What was the second part?

322
00:35:59,225 --> 00:36:00,266
[SPEAKER_05]: Any what uses?

323
00:36:01,226 --> 00:36:02,986
[SPEAKER_01]: Whether there were any exigent.

324
00:36:03,806 --> 00:36:04,226
[SPEAKER_01]: Exigent.

325
00:36:04,566 --> 00:36:07,847
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

326
00:36:08,187 --> 00:36:11,868
[SPEAKER_01]: Second set of questions is around the GPS tracker.

327
00:36:14,159 --> 00:36:18,360
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm wondering if the Medford Police Department owns GPS trackers.

328
00:36:20,141 --> 00:36:21,161
[SPEAKER_01]: If so, how many?

329
00:36:21,181 --> 00:36:26,083
[SPEAKER_01]: And was their purchase or use cleared with city council?

330
00:36:27,343 --> 00:36:31,345
[SPEAKER_01]: And is there a policy, an internal policy on their use?

331
00:36:34,946 --> 00:36:38,227
[SPEAKER_01]: And a third set of questions is on FLOC.

332
00:36:39,688 --> 00:36:51,116
[SPEAKER_01]: I just want to say Medford People Power doesn't necessarily object to the acquisition of this data in pursuit of a criminal investigation, but we have questions about it.

333
00:36:52,957 --> 00:37:08,187
[SPEAKER_01]: We'd like to know, and I think that Chief Buckley hinted at the answer that we want to hear, but it wasn't clear, was the data only on specific vehicles or was it

334
00:37:08,867 --> 00:37:12,249
[SPEAKER_01]: bulk data gathered at particular times and locations.

335
00:37:17,971 --> 00:37:29,777
[SPEAKER_01]: Related, why would the Medford Police Department be interested in data gathered outside of Medford, which the flock data would be?

336
00:37:34,103 --> 00:37:41,784
[SPEAKER_01]: The data that was acquired, was it the data itself that was shared or was access to the system shared?

337
00:37:46,905 --> 00:37:51,266
[SPEAKER_01]: When and how was this use authorized?

338
00:37:54,227 --> 00:37:58,627
[SPEAKER_01]: And what was kind of the timeline between the

339
00:38:03,693 --> 00:38:09,534
[SPEAKER_01]: the need for the investigation, the request for the authorization, the authorization and the receipt of the data.

340
00:38:09,614 --> 00:38:13,315
[SPEAKER_01]: Like, you know, was that 15 minutes?

341
00:38:13,395 --> 00:38:15,176
[SPEAKER_01]: Was it four days?

342
00:38:15,376 --> 00:38:20,737
[SPEAKER_01]: Like, you know, how did that, how does that progress?

343
00:38:23,358 --> 00:38:24,238
[SPEAKER_01]: And that's it.

344
00:38:25,198 --> 00:38:25,598
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

345
00:38:25,899 --> 00:38:26,259
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

346
00:38:27,459 --> 00:38:31,820
[SPEAKER_05]: Jean, could I ask if you can isolate the questions that you had in your comment,

347
00:38:32,517 --> 00:38:44,601
[SPEAKER_05]: I'd like to just write them down and I think maybe the best way to address this as early as possible would be that I can address these questions if this makes sense to the police department.

348
00:38:45,722 --> 00:38:51,004
[SPEAKER_05]: If you feel that these are things that are addressable in this meeting we could do it now or we could do it over email.

349
00:38:51,997 --> 00:38:57,360
[SPEAKER_05]: You know, and kind of, but I think if we did it over email, it wouldn't be public to, you know, hear the answers.

350
00:38:57,440 --> 00:39:02,823
[SPEAKER_05]: But if there's anything that we need to like go back on, we can come back to later.

351
00:39:02,904 --> 00:39:05,105
[SPEAKER_05]: But I want to make sure I have all the questions collected.

352
00:39:05,125 --> 00:39:05,305
[SPEAKER_00]: Great.

353
00:39:05,845 --> 00:39:06,185
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

354
00:39:07,086 --> 00:39:07,786
[SPEAKER_00]: There's really two.

355
00:39:08,747 --> 00:39:13,390
[SPEAKER_00]: One is the last report provided a breakdown of the special notification forms.

356
00:39:15,851 --> 00:39:18,352
[SPEAKER_00]: So it wasn't included in this report.

357
00:39:19,552 --> 00:39:22,654
[SPEAKER_00]: What's the reason or can it be included in future reports?

358
00:39:25,875 --> 00:39:26,115
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

359
00:39:26,735 --> 00:39:38,420
[SPEAKER_00]: And then the second is has there been any times when an officer has been allowed to review footage in a case where there's possible misconduct by that officer?

360
00:39:40,121 --> 00:39:40,401
[SPEAKER_00]: Got it.

361
00:39:42,122 --> 00:39:42,402
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

362
00:39:51,247 --> 00:39:53,829
[SPEAKER_05]: Chief, would you be willing to address these questions now?

363
00:39:53,849 --> 00:39:55,170
[SPEAKER_02]: I can try.

364
00:39:56,610 --> 00:40:01,173
[SPEAKER_02]: Although I can't promise you I'll get everything that Barry asked at the end there.

365
00:40:01,213 --> 00:40:01,753
[SPEAKER_02]: That's okay.

366
00:40:02,013 --> 00:40:05,135
[SPEAKER_05]: It feels like, I don't know, are you guys lawyers?

367
00:40:07,457 --> 00:40:09,978
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay, so let's start with, okay.

368
00:40:10,878 --> 00:40:16,902
[SPEAKER_05]: So tools, GPS trackers, flock data, and facial recognition data.

369
00:40:17,263 --> 00:40:28,710
[SPEAKER_05]: that you access from other agencies and other cities and towns that are being accessed in accordance with other applicable legal authorities?

370
00:40:28,830 --> 00:40:30,851
[SPEAKER_05]: What authorities would you be referring to?

371
00:40:30,931 --> 00:40:35,333
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't know how to answer the question.

372
00:40:35,413 --> 00:40:36,234
[SPEAKER_02]: It's my authority.

373
00:40:36,314 --> 00:40:39,456
[SPEAKER_02]: It's our authority as police officers to do criminal investigations, right?

374
00:40:39,476 --> 00:40:42,657
[SPEAKER_02]: So we're empowered with certain authority under the law to

375
00:40:44,550 --> 00:40:50,736
[SPEAKER_02]: gather and investigate criminal access, but in other words, I'm going to try to use the example I used earlier.

376
00:40:50,776 --> 00:40:53,819
[SPEAKER_02]: Somerville had something on their camera and we were notified it.

377
00:40:54,459 --> 00:41:00,605
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't know that we need much more authority other than our police authorities investigating criminal activity to gather that data.

378
00:41:01,386 --> 00:41:02,707
[SPEAKER_02]: But we don't, in other words, we don't have to

379
00:41:03,554 --> 00:41:10,439
[SPEAKER_02]: file a report with the state or ask the city council, or they don't have to go up to the chief and say, hey, can we do this?

380
00:41:11,320 --> 00:41:15,303
[SPEAKER_02]: They have to comply with state and federal law when it comes to that.

381
00:41:15,423 --> 00:41:17,644
[SPEAKER_02]: That's pretty much how we do our business on a daily basis.

382
00:41:18,285 --> 00:41:29,293
[SPEAKER_05]: Any time that you're investigating something in which a crime was allegedly committed in Medford and somebody crossed a town line,

383
00:41:30,293 --> 00:41:35,237
[SPEAKER_05]: And it was necessary to follow up on that person.

384
00:41:35,257 --> 00:41:35,317
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes.

385
00:41:36,298 --> 00:41:40,802
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm not sure if this was a question, but you're leading to one of the questions I think I heard.

386
00:41:41,042 --> 00:41:41,242
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

387
00:41:41,482 --> 00:41:45,686
[SPEAKER_02]: Was crime isn't restricted to the borders of Medford.

388
00:41:45,746 --> 00:41:46,066
[SPEAKER_02]: Exactly.

389
00:41:46,086 --> 00:41:50,149
[SPEAKER_02]: Medford individuals aren't committing crimes in Medford only and then going back to their homes.

390
00:41:50,309 --> 00:41:50,470
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

391
00:41:51,392 --> 00:41:52,793
[SPEAKER_02]: There are people who come from out of state.

392
00:41:52,813 --> 00:41:54,354
[SPEAKER_02]: There are people who go from city to city.

393
00:41:54,414 --> 00:42:00,098
[SPEAKER_02]: It's quite often that people who commit a crime will leave the jurisdiction of the Medford Police Department.

394
00:42:00,958 --> 00:42:03,140
[SPEAKER_02]: That's what any sane criminal would do, right?

395
00:42:03,160 --> 00:42:04,801
[SPEAKER_02]: You don't want to go where they're looking for you.

396
00:42:06,782 --> 00:42:09,504
[SPEAKER_02]: But I think I should add this also.

397
00:42:10,725 --> 00:42:14,107
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, while I won't get into the criminal investigations,

398
00:42:15,273 --> 00:42:28,018
[SPEAKER_02]: and not even necessarily the type, but we're not using GPS or facial recognition or like floor camera data from another jurisdiction for like shoplifters.

399
00:42:28,458 --> 00:42:31,619
[SPEAKER_02]: These are for serious criminal investigations.

400
00:42:34,180 --> 00:42:38,542
[SPEAKER_02]: And they're well worth the effort for the point in time that we're doing this.

401
00:42:38,642 --> 00:42:41,483
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think that can't be lost in this sort of conversation.

402
00:42:41,924 --> 00:42:42,764
[SPEAKER_02]: We're not just saying, hey,

403
00:42:44,255 --> 00:42:45,996
[SPEAKER_02]: just happened, let's see if Somerville has on it.

404
00:42:46,056 --> 00:42:51,277
[SPEAKER_02]: It's not worth our time to do all this extra work unless it's a serious violation of a criminal offense.

405
00:42:51,917 --> 00:43:01,880
[SPEAKER_02]: There are victims that need to be defended and there are bad people that we need to capture for public safety purposes.

406
00:43:01,900 --> 00:43:04,161
[SPEAKER_05]: Is it something violent necessarily?

407
00:43:04,801 --> 00:43:06,242
[SPEAKER_02]: It is often something violent.

408
00:43:09,692 --> 00:43:11,693
[SPEAKER_05]: Got it.

409
00:43:11,973 --> 00:43:14,734
[SPEAKER_05]: Does the Medford Police Department own GPS trackers?

410
00:43:15,075 --> 00:43:15,455
[SPEAKER_02]: We do not.

411
00:43:15,975 --> 00:43:16,135
[SPEAKER_05]: No.

412
00:43:18,916 --> 00:43:19,196
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

413
00:43:20,817 --> 00:43:25,359
[SPEAKER_05]: Could you give us a quick, actually, this is not one of the questions, but could you give us a quick summary of what FLOC is?

414
00:43:26,900 --> 00:43:28,941
[SPEAKER_05]: Because we've been saying FLOC, we haven't talked about what it is.

415
00:43:29,121 --> 00:43:30,062
[SPEAKER_02]: Oh, I don't know what FLOC is.

416
00:43:30,082 --> 00:43:30,922
[SPEAKER_02]: We're not allowed to use it.

417
00:43:33,817 --> 00:43:35,920
[SPEAKER_02]: The Flock is a company, first of all, right?

418
00:43:36,020 --> 00:43:38,625
[SPEAKER_02]: But it's basically just a camera that can capture data, right?

419
00:43:39,607 --> 00:43:45,417
[SPEAKER_02]: And yes, I mean, I know one of the questions was are we gathering bulk data or individual data?

420
00:43:46,631 --> 00:43:49,413
[SPEAKER_02]: To the best of my knowledge, again, I don't do these criminal investigations.

421
00:43:49,693 --> 00:43:50,593
[SPEAKER_02]: We all understand that.

422
00:43:50,633 --> 00:44:00,799
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm not involved in every single one of these cases, but we're not saying, hey, give us all your cameras and all your data at one time just so we can kind of skim through it and see who's doing what out there.

423
00:44:01,560 --> 00:44:03,421
[SPEAKER_02]: We don't have the time of the day to do this stuff, right?

424
00:44:03,441 --> 00:44:04,561
[SPEAKER_02]: Some of it's just practical.

425
00:44:05,622 --> 00:44:10,585
[SPEAKER_02]: If we are looking for a red Prius at 10.50 in the morning, that's what we're looking for.

426
00:44:11,325 --> 00:44:19,710
[SPEAKER_02]: And we'll have a general idea that they drove down, say, Warner Street into the city of Somerville, and we're very specific about what we're looking for in most cases.

427
00:44:20,271 --> 00:44:24,914
[SPEAKER_02]: And again, not for petty criminal offenses.

428
00:44:25,334 --> 00:44:40,343
[SPEAKER_02]: But flock cameras are a general system that, you know, to a lot of degree, they provide a safer environment for municipalities when it comes to conducting public safety.

429
00:44:41,539 --> 00:44:48,122
[SPEAKER_02]: This isn't the day, you know, that we have, you know, 150, 200 police officers here, right?

430
00:44:48,462 --> 00:44:54,965
[SPEAKER_02]: We have more and more responsibilities with less officers, and technology helps with that, right?

431
00:44:55,045 --> 00:44:55,886
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, every single day.

432
00:44:55,906 --> 00:44:58,287
[SPEAKER_02]: We're not still writing things with pen and paper anymore, right?

433
00:44:58,307 --> 00:44:59,588
[SPEAKER_02]: We're typing into our laptops.

434
00:44:59,608 --> 00:45:00,428
[SPEAKER_02]: That's technology.

435
00:45:00,488 --> 00:45:01,448
[SPEAKER_02]: It's just advancements.

436
00:45:02,189 --> 00:45:04,570
[SPEAKER_02]: Flock technology has the ability to be able to say,

437
00:45:05,413 --> 00:45:09,954
[SPEAKER_02]: I capture it, let's say we put a flock camera in Method Square, it will record what's going through there.

438
00:45:09,994 --> 00:45:20,057
[SPEAKER_02]: But when we need to find that red Prius who just committed, say, an armed robbery, we have specific times and understandings of when they may go through that, and it could capture plate data and give us the information.

439
00:45:20,917 --> 00:45:32,840
[SPEAKER_02]: It's a simple breakdown of it, but, you know, what I, we don't have flock cameras, so I don't, you know, this isn't, I don't want to offer this as a pro or a defense of the situation, but that's basically what they are.

440
00:45:33,493 --> 00:45:39,937
[SPEAKER_05]: So they are cameras that connect to each other and then they make like kind of a web of visual.

441
00:45:40,257 --> 00:45:46,741
[SPEAKER_02]: Well they can but they're not always right so like I've seen you know a lot of communities that just keep it's like regulated just in-house.

442
00:45:47,302 --> 00:45:47,542
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay.

443
00:45:47,702 --> 00:45:50,884
[SPEAKER_02]: Most of this most communities do that right we're not sharing.

444
00:45:53,893 --> 00:46:06,984
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm careful when I talk technology because I'm probably the worst, but it is often expensive and dangerous to share your data with everybody at any given time, and most public safety agencies don't do that.

445
00:46:10,768 --> 00:46:11,969
[SPEAKER_02]: When used right, it's a great tool.

446
00:46:18,208 --> 00:46:30,611
[SPEAKER_05]: So when you request data, if you're not given access, are you given access to the whole system or just to the data that you request or the question answered that you ask?

447
00:46:32,611 --> 00:46:33,852
[SPEAKER_02]: So I haven't done it personally.

448
00:46:34,012 --> 00:46:35,192
[SPEAKER_02]: I'll go back to what I said before.

449
00:46:35,212 --> 00:46:36,452
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm not actually doing this.

450
00:46:36,752 --> 00:46:39,533
[SPEAKER_02]: But again, we are looking for specific things.

451
00:46:41,616 --> 00:46:44,298
[SPEAKER_02]: We're not going to say, hey, let's go look at every camera.

452
00:46:44,878 --> 00:46:45,899
[SPEAKER_02]: I hate to pick on Somerville.

453
00:46:45,959 --> 00:46:47,640
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm just using them as example because they're next door.

454
00:46:47,760 --> 00:46:51,843
[SPEAKER_02]: So let's go look at every camera at Somerville and see if we see a suspicious car that's driving by.

455
00:46:52,724 --> 00:46:53,785
[SPEAKER_02]: That's just a waste of time.

456
00:46:54,645 --> 00:46:56,647
[SPEAKER_02]: So we use them for specific circumstances.

457
00:46:56,667 --> 00:47:00,329
[SPEAKER_05]: You would have to come to them with something that you've identified.

458
00:47:00,730 --> 00:47:01,490
[SPEAKER_02]: Or they come to us.

459
00:47:01,610 --> 00:47:02,591
[SPEAKER_05]: Or they come to you.

460
00:47:05,462 --> 00:47:08,525
[SPEAKER_05]: What's the timeline for something along those lines?

461
00:47:08,625 --> 00:47:14,630
[SPEAKER_05]: If you were to identify a kind of car that somebody was looking for, how fast is the turnaround?

462
00:47:14,990 --> 00:47:17,392
[SPEAKER_02]: It could vary.

463
00:47:17,813 --> 00:47:23,137
[SPEAKER_02]: We may not develop a suspect vehicle in a criminal investigation for a month or two later.

464
00:47:23,538 --> 00:47:23,718
[SPEAKER_03]: Right.

465
00:47:24,098 --> 00:47:24,319
[SPEAKER_02]: Right?

466
00:47:24,419 --> 00:47:26,580
[SPEAKER_02]: So there's no real way to answer that question.

467
00:47:28,014 --> 00:47:33,878
[SPEAKER_02]: But let's say an incident happened right now, and we know that the vehicle, we had concrete proof that the vehicle drove into the city of Somerville.

468
00:47:34,218 --> 00:47:35,179
[SPEAKER_02]: We could call Somerville.

469
00:47:35,199 --> 00:47:35,940
[SPEAKER_02]: They could look at it.

470
00:47:36,100 --> 00:47:38,041
[SPEAKER_02]: It probably would take a half hour to an hour.

471
00:47:38,381 --> 00:47:38,782
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't know.

472
00:47:38,902 --> 00:47:41,584
[SPEAKER_02]: Again, I don't do this on a daily basis.

473
00:47:41,644 --> 00:47:47,368
[SPEAKER_02]: And when I was doing criminal investigations, all the cameras were like video cameras.

474
00:47:48,709 --> 00:47:50,591
[SPEAKER_02]: But in general, it doesn't work that fast.

475
00:47:50,611 --> 00:47:52,252
[SPEAKER_02]: Like we're not that into it.

476
00:47:52,332 --> 00:47:54,894
[SPEAKER_02]: Nor would we be that sort of,

477
00:47:57,478 --> 00:48:00,500
[SPEAKER_02]: It would depend on the violence and the extremity of the crime.

478
00:48:00,640 --> 00:48:02,421
[SPEAKER_02]: That would really push things.

479
00:48:02,501 --> 00:48:05,323
[SPEAKER_02]: But there's really no, there's no way of determining.

480
00:48:06,244 --> 00:48:08,566
[SPEAKER_02]: Again, because facts change at all different times.

481
00:48:08,926 --> 00:48:09,166
[SPEAKER_05]: Got it.

482
00:48:10,227 --> 00:48:11,608
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

483
00:48:12,608 --> 00:48:18,272
[SPEAKER_05]: For Gene's questions, the last report had a breakdown of the special notification forms, but that wasn't here this time.

484
00:48:19,033 --> 00:48:19,433
[SPEAKER_05]: Why not?

485
00:48:19,553 --> 00:48:21,815
[SPEAKER_05]: And is it possible to get it in the next report?

486
00:48:22,633 --> 00:48:24,735
[SPEAKER_02]: I believe it's still possible to do this, right?

487
00:48:24,815 --> 00:48:28,858
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, it's just data that we have to kind of extract and go through all of those reports.

488
00:48:28,878 --> 00:48:36,083
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think we did it the first time to, you know, kind of give us an idea of what's going on.

489
00:48:36,263 --> 00:48:39,565
[SPEAKER_02]: And again, we do review our special notification forms, et cetera.

490
00:48:42,167 --> 00:48:45,409
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't want to put work on them, but I think it's still something that could be possible.

491
00:48:45,489 --> 00:48:46,130
[SPEAKER_02]: I just want to note.

492
00:48:47,427 --> 00:48:51,972
[SPEAKER_02]: repeating myself, but the body-worn camera report is essentially just an internal document.

493
00:48:51,992 --> 00:48:55,476
[SPEAKER_02]: It's not, like, required as part of this, and I'm not saying what it is.

494
00:48:55,536 --> 00:48:59,341
[SPEAKER_02]: In general, it can be helpful, but I think we could still provide that notification.

495
00:48:59,381 --> 00:49:04,467
[SPEAKER_02]: But as we advance in our use of this technology of body-worn camera, these things

496
00:49:05,946 --> 00:49:29,375
[SPEAKER_02]: are becoming like sort of rote, like everyday things, we know what's happening, we know what it is, and we're not, if we see like, wait, this special notification form said something so bizarre that we didn't understand, that's what we're gonna sort of look into, but if it's the regular everyday, like, okay, we've seen this before, we've seen this before, we keep track of them, of course, but we, I don't think we can, I don't think we generate it in this time, but it's not impossible to do.

497
00:49:31,416 --> 00:49:33,637
[SPEAKER_05]: Another thing I'd like to note is that

498
00:49:34,630 --> 00:49:47,496
[SPEAKER_05]: The requirements of this report aren't the same as something that you might want to keep track of in a body-worn camera report, which we saw a lot of last time, last year, because the body-worn camera program was very new.

499
00:49:48,416 --> 00:49:54,379
[SPEAKER_05]: And the CCOPS report is really much more, it's not about the success of the body-worn camera program.

500
00:49:54,459 --> 00:50:03,863
[SPEAKER_05]: It's about, is the body-worn camera program and every other bit of surveillance, including the parking, you know, is it,

501
00:50:05,247 --> 00:50:30,583
[SPEAKER_05]: stepping past what its intention is, which is to allow police officers to successfully carry out their work while being held accountable for doing it the right way without inadvertently taking and keeping images of our residents unnecessarily invading their privacy and

502
00:50:32,667 --> 00:50:33,647
[SPEAKER_05]: uh, violating their rights.

503
00:50:34,087 --> 00:50:38,268
[SPEAKER_05]: So that's what this report is about, is, is, is it going too far in that direction?

504
00:50:38,608 --> 00:50:41,329
[SPEAKER_05]: So it's not really about, like, all the stuff about body-worn cameras.

505
00:50:41,589 --> 00:50:46,310
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's, I think, where it, like, the first version of this report was kind of a little bit of both.

506
00:50:46,890 --> 00:50:54,692
[SPEAKER_05]: And maybe that's why this version is shorter and, uh, more specifically about, uh, is it overstepping?

507
00:50:55,279 --> 00:50:56,940
[SPEAKER_05]: and answering those questions exactly.

508
00:50:58,260 --> 00:51:09,523
[SPEAKER_05]: So if there are things that we may like to see in the body-worn camera report, that may just be like something that's not in the ordinance and not required of this report.

509
00:51:13,064 --> 00:51:13,985
[SPEAKER_05]: I mean, I'm just saying that.

510
00:51:14,825 --> 00:51:15,605
[SPEAKER_05]: That's not a question.

511
00:51:17,986 --> 00:51:18,926
[SPEAKER_05]: And we can look at that again.

512
00:51:18,966 --> 00:51:22,527
[SPEAKER_05]: I mean, it's like we can ask for it, but it doesn't mean that you're required to do it.

513
00:51:25,474 --> 00:51:30,361
[SPEAKER_02]: But to that point, we are making sure that we're not here to invade anybody's privacy.

514
00:51:30,381 --> 00:51:30,641
[SPEAKER_02]: No, I know.

515
00:51:30,841 --> 00:51:31,883
[SPEAKER_02]: I'll make a notification.

516
00:51:31,903 --> 00:51:32,524
[SPEAKER_02]: Inadvertently.

517
00:51:32,544 --> 00:51:34,166
[SPEAKER_02]: Just as an opportunity to.

518
00:51:34,747 --> 00:51:36,890
[SPEAKER_02]: And we keep track of that.

519
00:51:36,910 --> 00:51:40,155
[SPEAKER_02]: And eventually, I know the question was mentioned about retentions.

520
00:51:40,735 --> 00:51:42,076
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, we have a retention schedule.

521
00:51:42,096 --> 00:51:42,837
[SPEAKER_02]: It's in our policy.

522
00:51:42,877 --> 00:51:47,480
[SPEAKER_02]: I can't give it to you and dictate it to you all right now, but everything has a lifespan and they just go away.

523
00:51:47,540 --> 00:51:48,661
[SPEAKER_02]: They just delete.

524
00:51:49,622 --> 00:51:52,163
[SPEAKER_02]: And the second part of that is no one has access to this.

525
00:51:52,384 --> 00:52:00,470
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, outside of our police department, and we have the systems in play that I've already talked about on checks and balances and who has access.

526
00:52:01,270 --> 00:52:02,451
[SPEAKER_02]: Nobody has access to this.

527
00:52:02,491 --> 00:52:04,071
[SPEAKER_02]: Motorola doesn't have access to this.

528
00:52:04,131 --> 00:52:05,712
[SPEAKER_02]: The state doesn't have access to this.

529
00:52:06,273 --> 00:52:08,694
[SPEAKER_02]: The Middlesex District Attorney's Office doesn't have access.

530
00:52:08,734 --> 00:52:15,237
[SPEAKER_02]: The feds don't have access unless we physically hand it to them and we are only doing that through proper public records requests.

531
00:52:16,378 --> 00:52:16,758
[SPEAKER_05]: And warrants.

532
00:52:17,958 --> 00:52:19,779
[SPEAKER_02]: And warrants, but we're not really getting those.

533
00:52:19,899 --> 00:52:20,139
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

534
00:52:20,760 --> 00:52:21,000
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

535
00:52:21,900 --> 00:52:22,120
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

536
00:52:22,781 --> 00:52:29,304
[SPEAKER_05]: Have there been times when an officer was allowed to review footage in a case where there was misconduct, known misconduct by that officer?

537
00:52:30,630 --> 00:52:31,651
[SPEAKER_02]: This is an interesting answer.

538
00:52:32,612 --> 00:52:33,293
[SPEAKER_02]: The answer is yes.

539
00:52:34,794 --> 00:52:41,120
[SPEAKER_02]: But you have to remember, though, if most misconduct or a lot of misconduct will come out of, say, a police action.

540
00:52:41,869 --> 00:52:50,211
[SPEAKER_02]: And in which case, the police officer would have already written a report, has already had access to their body-worn camera, has reviewed it, wrote their report.

541
00:52:50,711 --> 00:52:56,193
[SPEAKER_02]: And maybe a day, week, month later, somebody comes in and files a complaint against that police officer.

542
00:52:56,253 --> 00:52:58,433
[SPEAKER_02]: So at that point, we can't really do anything about it.

543
00:52:58,573 --> 00:52:59,914
[SPEAKER_05]: They've already done the review.

544
00:53:00,034 --> 00:53:01,834
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, they've already seen the body-worn camera.

545
00:53:01,854 --> 00:53:02,895
[SPEAKER_02]: They've already written the report.

546
00:53:03,515 --> 00:53:06,796
[SPEAKER_02]: Complaints don't generate immediately, sometimes after an incident.

547
00:53:09,348 --> 00:53:13,909
[SPEAKER_02]: Having said that, there have been times and instances of potential misconduct, right?

548
00:53:14,350 --> 00:53:15,450
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, we say it's misconduct.

549
00:53:16,350 --> 00:53:19,531
[SPEAKER_02]: And this is where it gets interesting.

550
00:53:20,391 --> 00:53:32,435
[SPEAKER_02]: Even though they are allowed to, by policy, review their policy, officers and their attorneys, their representative unions, are electing to not watch the camera until after they answer their questions.

551
00:53:33,125 --> 00:53:41,327
[SPEAKER_02]: And their theory is that we want to dictate to you exactly what we recall in this instance as fresh as we can remember it offhand.

552
00:53:42,007 --> 00:53:46,868
[SPEAKER_02]: And I reserve my right to, you know, modify my statement after I watch the body-worn camera.

553
00:53:47,068 --> 00:53:50,149
[SPEAKER_02]: That is becoming more and more of a practical thing.

554
00:53:51,049 --> 00:53:57,670
[SPEAKER_02]: And that's part of their, I don't want to call it the defense, but that's part of their representation in a potential misconduct.

555
00:53:58,030 --> 00:54:00,051
[SPEAKER_02]: So it's a good question.

556
00:54:00,491 --> 00:54:01,191
[SPEAKER_02]: The answer is yes.

557
00:54:02,417 --> 00:54:10,961
[SPEAKER_02]: It's an evolving situation where I think attorneys and unions and offices are starting to say, hey, I want to get a statement in right away.

558
00:54:12,061 --> 00:54:21,005
[SPEAKER_02]: And then I'll watch my body-worn camera and modify my statement, which we will allow them to do also, even though they have the right to watch that camera ahead of time.

559
00:54:22,286 --> 00:54:22,566
[SPEAKER_05]: Interesting.

560
00:54:24,047 --> 00:54:24,907
[SPEAKER_02]: So they're doing it on their own.

561
00:54:28,508 --> 00:54:30,029
[SPEAKER_02]: I threw you a curve ball with that one, didn't I?

562
00:54:30,049 --> 00:54:31,551
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, it was interesting.

563
00:54:32,352 --> 00:54:33,192
[SPEAKER_05]: I mean, it's smart to do.

564
00:54:34,454 --> 00:54:34,834
[SPEAKER_05]: OK.

565
00:54:36,836 --> 00:54:38,437
[SPEAKER_05]: Councillor Singh did join us.

566
00:54:39,498 --> 00:54:45,564
[SPEAKER_05]: Do we have any other comments from city councillors?

567
00:54:46,985 --> 00:54:48,626
[SPEAKER_05]: Councillor Singh does want to say something.

568
00:54:49,768 --> 00:54:50,248
[SPEAKER_05]: Councillor Singh?

569
00:54:52,720 --> 00:54:57,364
[SPEAKER_03]: Hi, thank you for joining us, Chief Buckley, and sorry I'm a little late to this.

570
00:54:57,524 --> 00:55:00,447
[SPEAKER_03]: My day job has been kind of crazy recently.

571
00:55:02,248 --> 00:55:06,972
[SPEAKER_03]: I was wondering about the disproportionate impact.

572
00:55:07,512 --> 00:55:11,355
[SPEAKER_03]: The report concludes that no community was disproportionately impacted.

573
00:55:12,096 --> 00:55:16,660
[SPEAKER_03]: Would you be able to describe the methodology behind that assessment?

574
00:55:17,740 --> 00:55:18,981
[SPEAKER_03]: What data was reviewed?

575
00:55:19,362 --> 00:55:19,782
[SPEAKER_03]: By whom?

576
00:55:21,705 --> 00:55:32,754
[SPEAKER_03]: I think without demographic data on who's reported or investigated using these technologies, it's a bit difficult for us as a council to independently evaluate that conclusions.

577
00:55:32,834 --> 00:55:34,736
[SPEAKER_03]: I was wondering if you could speak to it to that.

578
00:55:37,438 --> 00:55:38,599
[SPEAKER_02]: I could try the.

579
00:55:42,795 --> 00:55:53,774
[SPEAKER_02]: When body work cameras were first discussed in the city of Medford, there were several proposals, I don't remember from who at this point in time, to conduct these studies on disproportionate impact.

580
00:55:55,032 --> 00:56:09,605
[SPEAKER_02]: in the community and they had all of this information such as gathering GPS data and where in the city was the body, where's the body, where camera footage taken and match that up to demographic, just information that we couldn't possibly do, right?

581
00:56:09,685 --> 00:56:17,092
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think everyone grew to understanding that that sort of in-depth study would be impossible and so,

582
00:56:17,803 --> 00:56:21,964
[SPEAKER_02]: Right now, how we're measuring it is part by audit, right?

583
00:56:22,584 --> 00:56:35,107
[SPEAKER_02]: And again, we do this audit of three of each case, but also there's some three to 400 public records requests every time that we have to edit and review and we have lieutenants and an officer who reviews the body-worn cameras and looking over those things.

584
00:56:35,507 --> 00:56:37,527
[SPEAKER_02]: And we can see and develop patents.

585
00:56:39,327 --> 00:56:44,609
[SPEAKER_02]: And also the final determination would be how many complaints we're receiving from the public on this, right?

586
00:56:44,649 --> 00:56:46,789
[SPEAKER_02]: And where those complaints are emanating from.

587
00:56:47,329 --> 00:56:57,315
[SPEAKER_02]: That's why we haven't seen anything that has suggested to us that the community is being disproportionately affected by our use of body-worn camera.

588
00:56:58,656 --> 00:57:02,178
[SPEAKER_02]: I know it's written into the C-Corp's ordinance, and I've argued this from day one.

589
00:57:02,678 --> 00:57:10,462
[SPEAKER_02]: The whole argument, the whole question of how do we determine it is like, I'm not saying we won't do it.

590
00:57:10,482 --> 00:57:11,863
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm just saying how do we do it?

591
00:57:11,883 --> 00:57:14,304
[SPEAKER_02]: I think we're doing it well now with what we have.

592
00:57:16,479 --> 00:57:19,440
[SPEAKER_02]: unless you get sort of complaints or we notice it ourselves.

593
00:57:19,760 --> 00:57:21,380
[SPEAKER_02]: And keep in mind, we do that anyway, right?

594
00:57:21,400 --> 00:57:29,663
[SPEAKER_02]: Like we know if we have an officer who's just arresting a certain demographic or just making car stops, we're picking up on that.

595
00:57:29,723 --> 00:57:32,684
[SPEAKER_02]: We see this and we have people in lines that are keeping track of this data.

596
00:57:33,384 --> 00:57:37,745
[SPEAKER_02]: And the same thing sort of would pop up on body-worn cameras.

597
00:57:37,945 --> 00:57:42,067
[SPEAKER_02]: But I recognize that the intent of that is a lot more than what I just said, right?

598
00:57:42,087 --> 00:57:43,107
[SPEAKER_02]: There's a lot more to it.

599
00:57:43,647 --> 00:57:49,651
[SPEAKER_02]: It's just that we've discussed this in the city and other communities have discussed it, and they, we don't even know how to do that, right?

600
00:57:49,891 --> 00:57:51,672
[SPEAKER_02]: And yes, it's part of the CCOPS ordinance.

601
00:57:52,193 --> 00:58:04,801
[SPEAKER_02]: So we answer it as best we can, and we do our best to kind of make sure what we have, but there's no real clear-cut reason or process for us to go through and do that.

602
00:58:11,182 --> 00:58:14,264
[SPEAKER_03]: I just wanted to say thanks for the answer.

603
00:58:14,565 --> 00:58:18,708
[SPEAKER_03]: I think it's something for us all to think a little bit more about.

604
00:58:19,188 --> 00:58:29,616
[SPEAKER_03]: I know, I understand it's, you know, it can be difficult for you as an executive to read that and to decide how to go forward.

605
00:58:29,776 --> 00:58:33,899
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm hoping us as a community that will sometimes help you

606
00:58:35,393 --> 00:58:36,454
[SPEAKER_03]: think through that as well.

607
00:58:37,435 --> 00:58:41,658
[SPEAKER_03]: I have to assume that there are folks who might have questions.

608
00:58:41,778 --> 00:58:43,199
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't want to hog the time.

609
00:58:47,242 --> 00:58:50,905
[SPEAKER_05]: Sorry, I'm having a hard time understanding what you're saying, Councilor Sang.

610
00:58:50,985 --> 00:58:52,126
[SPEAKER_05]: Could you say that one more time?

611
00:58:53,987 --> 00:58:57,029
[SPEAKER_03]: Sorry, my audio recently is a bit crazy.

612
00:58:57,069 --> 00:58:57,570
[SPEAKER_03]: Does this work?

613
00:58:59,483 --> 00:59:03,586
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, I also can just read the, if I stand up, I can read the captions.

614
00:59:03,786 --> 00:59:04,747
[SPEAKER_05]: Go ahead, say it again.

615
00:59:05,567 --> 00:59:16,054
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, I was just saying, I understand that thinking through disproportionate impact is something that is really difficult because it can, it can touch a lot of things, mean a lot of things.

616
00:59:16,074 --> 00:59:19,276
[SPEAKER_03]: There's a lot of bigger points that could be collected or used.

617
00:59:20,036 --> 00:59:24,739
[SPEAKER_03]: And I just wanted to thank Chief Buckley for his answers.

618
00:59:24,919 --> 00:59:25,600
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm sure that

619
00:59:26,288 --> 00:59:36,999
[SPEAKER_03]: Folks will have a lot of ideas on what we can track and hopefully as a community and as a council, we can help Chief Buckley think through it as well and upgrade him deeper.

620
00:59:37,380 --> 00:59:46,910
[SPEAKER_03]: And then I said that I don't want to hog my time because I know that folks in the community, in the audience, might have questions.

621
00:59:48,077 --> 00:59:49,078
[SPEAKER_05]: Oh, for sure.

622
00:59:50,178 --> 00:59:53,420
[SPEAKER_05]: No, we have actually already done our public comment.

623
00:59:53,440 --> 00:59:54,200
[SPEAKER_05]: This meeting started at 630.

624
00:59:55,400 --> 00:59:56,001
[SPEAKER_05]: Love you so much.

625
00:59:59,943 --> 01:00:11,048
[SPEAKER_05]: I think one thing to note about the question about folks being disproportionately impacted is that not being

626
01:00:13,021 --> 01:00:23,461
[SPEAKER_05]: racist or prejudiced or uh uh it's really hard to disprove it's hard to prove a negative it's hard to you know it's it's hard to say that you're like you're

627
01:00:25,744 --> 01:00:40,774
[SPEAKER_05]: being even-handed with your traffic stops or the way that you react to investigations or respond to domestic violence calls or arrest people or don't.

628
01:00:41,374 --> 01:00:42,815
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think it's probably a good sign.

629
01:00:42,855 --> 01:00:46,137
[SPEAKER_05]: If you can't really tell, if you can't see a pattern, that's great.

630
01:00:46,958 --> 01:00:49,339
[SPEAKER_05]: We would like to see more of that.

631
01:00:50,380 --> 01:00:53,362
[SPEAKER_05]: So whatever kind of records you're keeping, keep doing it.

632
01:00:55,003 --> 01:01:00,465
[SPEAKER_05]: keep being confused about how to show that you're not seeming racist.

633
01:01:00,665 --> 01:01:01,566
[SPEAKER_05]: We would love to.

634
01:01:01,586 --> 01:01:02,866
[SPEAKER_05]: We would love to carry that forward.

635
01:01:03,286 --> 01:01:24,175
[SPEAKER_02]: And again, I just want to reflect that I recognize that that is a much larger question than as we're simply talking about it, but it's really the only way to talk about it now, because it is a it's a difficult and confusing sort of dynamic and continuing to continuing to keep the conversation going and continuing to keep all the officers aware of like of like how

636
01:01:26,607 --> 01:01:46,276
[SPEAKER_05]: how it's being reported on and how front of mind it needs to be and that it, you know, professional development and constant, you know, opportunities to train and retrain and, you know, keep best practices in mind and all of that stuff being part of the conversation as you move forward is probably the best way to keep doing it.

637
01:01:47,800 --> 01:01:54,763
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think that, again, it's very difficult to prove that you're not doing something.

638
01:01:54,843 --> 01:02:02,327
[SPEAKER_05]: So I appreciate that we can continue to have that discussion.

639
01:02:04,328 --> 01:02:07,269
[SPEAKER_05]: Are there any other comments from counselors?

640
01:02:09,610 --> 01:02:10,931
[SPEAKER_05]: Counselor Sang, you do still have your hand up.

641
01:02:10,951 --> 01:02:11,971
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you want to say something else?

642
01:02:13,132 --> 01:02:13,452
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, no.

643
01:02:13,512 --> 01:02:14,072
[SPEAKER_03]: Sorry.

644
01:02:14,092 --> 01:02:15,493
[SPEAKER_03]: I didn't realize it was still up.

645
01:02:16,877 --> 01:02:17,417
[SPEAKER_05]: We're doing great.

646
01:02:18,678 --> 01:02:19,039
OK.

647
01:02:19,419 --> 01:02:20,540
[SPEAKER_03]: It's one of those days.

648
01:02:23,482 --> 01:02:23,722
[SPEAKER_05]: Same.

649
01:02:25,043 --> 01:02:26,084
[SPEAKER_05]: OK.

650
01:02:26,244 --> 01:02:31,027
[SPEAKER_05]: Do we have any motions from counselors?

651
01:02:31,347 --> 01:02:31,608
[SPEAKER_05]: Anyone?

652
01:02:33,809 --> 01:02:34,770
[SPEAKER_05]: Does anyone have a motion?

653
01:02:37,172 --> 01:02:38,853
[SPEAKER_05]: Counselor Callahan.

654
01:02:39,033 --> 01:02:39,393
[SPEAKER_05]: Oh, wait.

655
01:02:39,433 --> 01:02:41,274
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you want to say something?

656
01:02:42,115 --> 01:02:42,415
[SPEAKER_05]: Great.

657
01:02:43,316 --> 01:02:44,677
[SPEAKER_05]: Everybody's doing great.

658
01:02:45,157 --> 01:02:45,838
[SPEAKER_05]: Counselor Callahan.

659
01:02:47,400 --> 01:02:50,243
[SPEAKER_06]: I assume you keep this paper in committee because we review it every year.

660
01:02:51,103 --> 01:02:52,885
[SPEAKER_05]: I think you can approve this report.

661
01:02:53,045 --> 01:02:56,067
[SPEAKER_05]: Approve the report, keep the paper in committee, and adjourn.

662
01:02:56,788 --> 01:02:57,208
[SPEAKER_05]: Excellent.

663
01:02:57,368 --> 01:03:01,792
[SPEAKER_05]: On the motion of Councillor Callaghan to approve the report, keep the paper in committee, and adjourn.

664
01:03:01,832 --> 01:03:02,552
[SPEAKER_05]: Do we have a second?

665
01:03:03,133 --> 01:03:03,653
[SPEAKER_03]: Seconded.

666
01:03:04,554 --> 01:03:06,015
[SPEAKER_05]: Seconded by Councillor Sang.

667
01:03:07,856 --> 01:03:09,077
[SPEAKER_05]: Mr. Clerk, can you please call the roll?

668
01:03:10,578 --> 01:03:11,339
[SPEAKER_04]: Councillor Callaghan.

669
01:03:14,201 --> 01:03:15,062
[SPEAKER_04]: Councillor Scott Pelley.

670
01:03:15,622 --> 01:03:15,903
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

671
01:03:18,732 --> 01:03:19,474
[SPEAKER_04]: Councilor Singh.

672
01:03:20,016 --> 01:03:20,297
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

673
01:03:23,467 --> 01:03:25,855
[SPEAKER_04]: Councilor Lemming is absent.

674
01:03:26,918 --> 01:03:28,784
[SPEAKER_04]: And Vice President Lazaro.

675
01:03:29,245 --> 01:03:29,566
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes.

676
01:03:31,693 --> 01:03:33,017
[SPEAKER_05]: In the affirmative, one absent.

